  <title translate="true">STL</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword translate="true">STL</keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table styleclass="PopupTable" rowcount="1" colcount="1" style="width:450px;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">A </text><text styleclass="Popup Box2" translate="true">STL</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> file-type is derived from the word &quot;Stereolithography.&quot; The </text><text styleclass="Popup Box2" translate="true">STL</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> file-type gives the xyz coordinates of the vertices and normals of triangles that describe the surface of the 3D object.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">Each triangle is defined by its normal and three points at its vertices. You can have a coarse, fine or custom number of triangles and vertices.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">The number of triangles you need is a balance between unmanageable file size (too many triangles) and a well-defined model with reasonably smooth curved geometries.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#ff6600;" /></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="Popup Box2" translate="true">STL </text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">File should be saved as a Binary file with units of Meters</text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
  </body>
